2. The "Falling Particle" Paradox (Lawful Time Dilation)
The famous paradox of the muon is that it is created kilometers above the Earth but has a lifetime of only 2.2 microseconds. At low speed, it should decay long before reaching the ground. Yet, we observe it constantly hitting the surface.

Conventional View: This is explained by Special Relativity's time dilation (γ factor). The muon travels so fast (v≈c) that time slows down for it.

